  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Prayer in the Inner Sanctuary
  author: Guo Yu
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Shakyamuni is the mother of all sentient beings; the supreme truth reigns as sovereign over all scriptures. The drum's resonant thunder shakes the heavens—the Buddha's perfection transcends measure. Yet the earth's abundance grows through the boundless compassion of the Tathagata alone. If we pray with sincere devotion and diligent heart, the Buddha's sublime aid will not falter.

    I bow and reflect: I have shamefully served the Mandate of Heaven, yet encountered an age when fortune dims. Extravagance and profligacy have festered like rot in the nation's body; base desires and corrupt schemes have stripped the people bare. Inner traitors manipulate power while foreign armies stand at the border demanding account. When we were commanded to suppress rebellion and move the capital, brigands scattered and plundered the kingdom's stores, vanishing like thieves in the night. Great armies encamped leave nothing but devastation—both public and private wealth reduced to ash. Morning brings no counsel for evening; we can only watch the autumn harvest, hoping it will come.

    Yet now the calamities of old have awakened, manifesting as cruel drought. When the fields most need rain to nurture their seedlings, thirty days pass with not a drop from heaven. The people suffer unbearably. Perhaps heaven takes pity. Yet the old vices persist—this scourge we have summoned upon ourselves. But surely punishment should fall upon the guilty, not extend to the innocent. The World-Honored One's compassion knows no bounds, and the celestial spirits cherish the highest good. If we genuinely confess and earnestly entreat, they will surely protect us without delay.

    We purify the inner sanctuary and perform the Buddha's rites. If we add true sincerity to this, we shall reach the Buddha's boundless resonance. I humbly pray: let the sun's rays withdraw their scorching fire and disperse the burning clouds. Let the rain spirits deliberate and shower us with sweet nectar like precious oil. May the withered be revived and the harvest end all blemish, bringing abundance great and true.
  footnotes:
    - Shakyamuni (능인, Neng ren) - the historical Buddha, literally meaning 'the Compassionate Sage'
    - The supreme truth (진체) - refers to ultimate Buddhist reality, fundamental to all Buddhist teachings
    - This appears to be a prayer composed during a period of national crisis, likely during the Mongol invasions or a subsequent dynasty transition, requesting divine intervention to end drought and restore the nation
